div.p:
 And I confer to this settlement these immunities: 
it is not to be entered (by royal officers without permission); 
not to be interfered with; 
not to be dug for salt; 
not to be controlled by the (superordinate) territory araṭṭhasaṁvinaIkaṁ:According to 392, this MIA form corresponds to Sanskrit arāṣṭrasāṃvinayika and refers to the freedom of the gift land from the administrative control to which the district in which it was situated was subject392. Even though it may seem counter-intuitive because of the double negation (a- and vi-), meanings of vinī such as “to instruct, to direct, to punish” allow this interpretation. See also 67-6; 149; 1994. Ther term also occurs in EIAD 172. For Pallava attestations, see 461. 
not to supply water-pots, boiled rice and cots; 
not to supply grass, betel leaves, vegetables, flowers, fruit, curd, milk, ghee and butter-milk; etc. 
With these exemptions and all other types of exemptions that have not been written due to erroneous omission, you shall exempt (this village) and (also) cause (it) to be exempted. Whosoever, failing to respect this edict, would cause trouble or harassment, of him we would not approve.’
